oompFamily.familyAbout: These little plastic bits are everywhere. They're Used for connecting wires to 2.54 mm (HEAD-I01, HEAL-I01) headers that are found on almost every PCB. While very handy, they are not keyed, so it's easy to plug them in backwards. Because of this it's best to avoid them when frequent connecting/un-connecting is required, or the design is to be used by untrained persons. While these connectors are everywhere they are (slowly) falling out of favor, being replaced by finer pitch connectors that allow denser connections.

These are absolutely everywhere. They're used for making board to board connections (when paired with HEAD-I01) or board to wire connections (when paired with CRHO-I01). While ubiquitous they are not always the best choice, The lack of a key means plugging them in backwards is always a worry, and when a lot of connections are required the pitch means a lot of real estate gets occupied.

These are rather rare, but can be super useful. One side of a standard 2.54 mm header is the perfect length for soldering, on these headers that side is the right length for plugging into a breadboard. They are also handy when connecting two female connectors (CRHO-I01) together. It means these are great when prototyping, allowing you to connect a wire with the right connector (CRHO-I01) to your breadboard, or butt two wires together even though they may not have been designed to connect to one another.

These ribbon cables on their own aren't very handy but when paired with the right crimp housing (CRHO-I01) become the answer to all your board connecting woes. The pre-crimped ends slide easily into a crimp housing making constructing custom cables a cinch, and the rainbow nature means it's easy to make your project colorful. While they are great, being un-keyed means plugging the constructed cable in backwards is possible, and with a 2.54 mm spacing quite a bit of real estate is used for multi-wire connections.

oompPart.name: 2.54 mm 1 Pin Black Crimp Housing
oompPart.oompAbout: This one pin housing is most often used in prototyping. Utilized when going from a multi-pin inline connector to a single pin.

oompPart.name: 2.54 mm 2 Pin Black Crimp Housing
oompPart.oompAbout: This two pin housing is most often used for connecting power to a project. When doing this it's best to use the convention of red for positive, and black for ground. Another common usage is when connecting an externally mounted button.

oompBundle.name: Premium Make Your Own Cable Kit
Massive Make Your Own Cable Kit

oompPart.name: 2.54 mm 3 Pin Black Crimp Housing
oompPart.oompAbout: This three pin housing is great for connecting externally mounted potentiometers. Also commonly found on hobby servos or any item requiring power (+,gnd) and a signal line. (WS2812 LED strings, analog temperature sensors etc.)

oompPart.name: 2.54 mm 4 Pin Black Crimp Housing
oompPart.oompAbout: These four pin connectors are often used simply when you find you have four wires that need connecting. That said a common usage is with data buses, most notably I2C (power (+/gnd) SDA, SCL), or they can also be found on stepper motors when they are being driven in bipolar mode (A+, A-, B+, B-).

oompPart.name: 2.54 mm 5 Pin Black Crimp Housing
oompPart.oompAbout: These five pin connectors are often used simply when you find you have five wires that need connecting. That said it can occasionally be found connecting an SPI bus (power (+,-), data, clock, slave select (SS)) or on a stepper motor being driven in uni-polar mode, with a shared central tap (A,B,C,D,tap)

oompPart.name: 2.54 mm 6 Pin Black Crimp Housing
oompPart.oompAbout: These six pin connectors are often used simply when you find you have six wires that need connecting. However they can occasionally be found on a stepper motor being driven in uni-polar mode (A,B,ABCom,C,D,CDCom), or are also handy when paired with a ten pin connector to attach a parallel LCD screen to a project.

oompPart.name: 2.54 mm 8 Pin Black Crimp Housing
oompPart.oompAbout: These eight pin connectors are often used simply when you find you have eight wires that need connecting. However if you know of a common usage please let us know.

oompPart.name: 2.54 mm 10 Pin Black Crimp Housing
oompPart.oompAbout: These ten pin connectors are often used simply when you find you have ten wires that need connecting. They are occasionally useful when paired with a six pin header, to connect a parallel LCD to a project.

oompPart.name: 2.54 mm 36 Pin Header
oompPart.oompAbout: These 36 pin strips are by far the most common length. They are designed to be snapped to any length (using either pliers or snips) so are the most useful to have in your toolbox.

oompPart.oompAbout: It's often tempting to use these 300 mm long cables, however they are best avoided if possible. That said they are useful at the early stage of a project where final placement is not known and the added length is an advantage.
